Fairly large refactor: do much more during the CFG lowering.In particular, lower all control-flow-involving expressions (such as boolops,nlist comprehensions, if expressions) into actual control flow.  This requiresnunfolding the AST into a flat structure, since the control-flow-expression cannbe nested inside other expressions, including other control-flow-expressions.nnThe IRGenerator was doing this before, but was leading to duplication becausenit's very similar to what the CFG generator already has to do.nnDoing this earlier in the pipeline means that more analysis passes can work onnthe lowered expressions, rather than having to be taught how they work.  Innparticular, the name analysis does not need to have to special case the factnthat list comprehensions may set names -- but aren't guaranteed to if they don'tnget executed or the iterator is empty.  I tried implementing list comprehensionsnwithout doing this, and a bunch of the work was in reimplementing the logic thatnthe analyzers already implement.nnAs a side benefit, deopts become much easier since the AST is already unfolded;nthis change gets rid of the messy fake-variable-setting way that the IRGeneratornwas unfolding the AST to get this same effect.n

Some small independent changesCan emit add/sub/etc instructions with 32-bit operands in addition to 8-bit nownCan get the RSP and RBP in rewriter1, for accessing scratch spacenChange some debugging outputnnFix a gc bug: if an object gets new'd, and takes a parameter that gets new'd, the sequence isn1) object space gets allocatedn2) parameter space gets allocatedn3) parameter gets constructedn4) object gets constructednThe bug is that the object construction is what initializes the GC header,nso if step #3 causes a collection, it can see that the allocation from step #1nhas an invalid header.nAs a workaround, always zero out the header in allocation, and skip blocks withnzeroed headers.nThe real solution is probably to have the GC manage the header itself rather thannexpecting the user to; this would mean that gc_alloc would take the allocation kind,nput that into the header, and then return a pointer to the post-header data sectionnof the allocation.n

Implement defaults, keywords, varargs and kwargsNot all exposed to python code yetnnThis commit is pretty large because it contains two separate but interrelated changes:n- Rewrite the function argument handling code (callCompiledFunction and resolveCLFunc)n  into a single callFunc that does its own rewriting, and support the new features.n-- this required a change of data representations, so instead of having each functionn   consist of variants with unrelated signatures, we can only have a single signature,n   but multiple type specializations of that signaturen- To do that, had to rewrite all of the stdlib functions that used signature-variationn  (ex range1 + range2 + range3) to be a single function that took default arguments, andn  then took action appropriately.n

Implement closuresImplementation is pretty straightforward for now:n- find all names that get accessed from a nested functionn- if any, create a closure object at function entryn- any time we set a name accessed from a nested function,n  update its value in the closuren- when evaluating a functiondef that needs a closure, attachn  the created closure to the created function object.nnClosures are currently passed as an extra argument before anynpython-level args, which I'm not convinced is the right strategy.nIt's works out fine but it feels messy to say that functionsncan have different C-level calling conventions.nIt felt worse to include the closure as part of the python-level argnpassing.nMaybe it should be passed after all the other arguments?nnClosures are currently just simple objects, on which we set and getnPython-level attributes.  The performance (which I haven't tested)nrelies on attribute access being made fast through the hidden-classninline caches.nnThere are a number of ways that this could be improved:n- be smarter about when we create the closure object, or when wen  update it.n- not create empty pass-through closuresn- give the closures a pre-defined shape, since we know at irgen-timen  what names can get set.  could probably avoid the inline cachen  machinery and also have better code.n

Some work on the Grand CAPI Unificationie trying to start running real C modules.  The goal has always been tonrun them without modification and without a proxy layer, and this is the first step.nnThe first issue is conversion between PyObject and our internal representation,nBox (needs to be renamed).  Once they have the same layout, some hacks werenneeded to make them seem like the same thing, even though we can attach C++nmethods on the Box side, but use PyObject in C code.nnThe next major issue was PyTypeObject, since the structure is directly exposed tonextensions.  I just added the similar fields to BoxedClass, so they can benused interchangeably; the real ones are the BoxedClass ones, but we'll migratenthem incrementally.nnThere's also the issue that PyTypeObject's are typically created statically,nso I added registerStaticRootMemory to the GC interface.nnAlso add in a smattering of other API functions, and the _sha module worksn(who cares if it's normally disabled).nnThe C API is quite constraining about choices of data structure implementation; it'snin direct conflict with the std::string API, for example.  For now, close our eyesnand let the C API modify the internal bytes of std::string.n

Make sure that we never reuse AST nodesWe currently specify execution state by the AST node thatnrepresents it, which means that we have to not reuse AST nodes.nPrevious to this patch, we were doing that, so this patchnfixes those up.nnThis patch isn't the cleanest since I think this whole approachnwill go away when we transition to a proper bytecode system.n

Compute intra-BB liveness informationWhen emitting frame information, we pass all currently-livenvariable names.  We clear dead register names at the end ofnevery basic block, but for long basic blocks we can end upnaccumulating many temporary names (one per sub expression).nThis ends up hugely increasing the LLVM compilation times sincenwe will pass hundreds of arguments to many different callsites.nnNow, we remove dead variable names as soon as they die.  (Note:nuser-visible names are always live since they can always be seennby the locals() function.)  This means that we pass many fewer valuesnas frame arguments.nnA better solution will be to have a real bytecode language whichnencodes such liveness information, instead of mostly-having it andnthen discarding it.n

Add 'runtime ics' to improve C++ runtime speedAn experimental way of making the runtime faster.  Previously, the C++nruntime was much slower than pure-Python code, since the Python codencan use the JIT to improve performance (through inline caches and typenspeculation).  This commit adds runtime ics, which are out-of-bandnpatchpoints that we can allocate from C++.  We insert them into thensame patchpoint system that gets used by the main JIT pipeline, sonthey get rewritten like any other patchpoint, but the lifetime and usengets controlled by the C++ code.nnThe trickiest part is getting the newly-allocated instruction regionsnto work with our exception handling; to make this work we have to emitn.eh_frame sections.  (A custom libunwind-based exception unwindernmight not have this requirement.)nnOtherwise it feels like a decent approach.  Right now just using it tonimplement class slots and then only using them in the pyElementsniterator; it's probably not the most direct or efficient way ofnimplementing that particular feature, but it has the benefit of beingngeneral and being useful for things such as binops which are notndirectly expressible in terms of class slots.nnThis commit adds the support without turning the feature on (nextncommit will turn it on), since there are a number of other changesnneeded.n

Improve threading fairnessPreviously, to allow other threads to acquire the GIL, we wouldnjust do a releaseGIL(); acquireGIL(); and hope that another threadnwould grab it.  The current thread has the best chance of grabbing thenGIL again, so I think what's been happening is that it would tend tonwin the race to reacquire and starve all the other threads.nnNow, the current thread is forced to wait for at least one othernthread to acquire the GIL before it can reaquire it.  This means thatnwe're at least fair between two threads, though not necessarily fairnbetween more than that (but at least it's more random and not as stackedntowards being unfair).n

Restructure the way we collect generator stacksPreviously it was pretty implicit where we rely on the fact that the generatornobject will exist on the previous stack, and once we notice the generatornits GC handler will crawl the generator stack.nnI think we also missed the generator's registers, but only the top generatornand only if it wasn't the current thread (was unable to reproduce this).nnNow, keep explicit track of all the previous stacks that a thread had been on.nThis cleans that up, and since things are explicit now, we can also tracknwhere we stopped executing on each stack.  We were doing this hackily for the mainnstack before, but now we can do that for generator stacks, which will letnus make those auto-growing as well.nnMy confidence in this change: low.n

Make it easier to run without frame introspectionTurning off frame introspection can make things easier tondebug, but will break features like tracebacks.nnIf we turn it off, instead of trying to collect a traceback andncrashing, just print out a warning and return an empty traceback.n

Change generator stack allocationPreviously, we just included a char[] buffer in the generator object,nand used that as the stack.nnNow, mmap() a dedicated stack segment for it.  Use MAP_GROWSDOWN so thatnthe stack is automatically expandable, but add a redzone 4MB down tonlimit the maximum stack size.n

Intern most codegen stringsMost importantly, intern all the strings we put into the AST* nodes.n(the AST_Module* owns them)nnThis should save us some memory, but it also improves performance prettynsubstantially since now we can do string comparisons very cheaply. It means that this diff is quite large, but it also makes it a lotnmore clear where we are making our string copies or have other room for optimization.n

This has a couple benefits:n1) they can participate in the existing sys.exc_info passing+handlingn2) we can enable a basic form of the traceback module.nn2 means that we can finally test our tracebacks support, since I was constantlynfixing one issue only to break it in another place.nn1 means that we now generate the right traceback for the current exception!nBefore this change, the traceback we would generate was determined using a differentnsystem than the exc_info-based exception raising, so sometimes they would divergenand be horribly confusing.nnThere's a pretty big limitation with the current implementation: our tracebacksndon't span the right stack frames.  In CPython, a traceback spans the stack framesnbetween the raise and the catch, but in Pyston the traceback includes all stack frames.nIt's not easy to provide this behavior, since the tracebacks are supposed to get updatednas they get rethrown through each stack frame.nnWe could do some complicated stuff in irgen to make sure this happens.  I think the betternbut more complicated approach is for us to create the custom exception unwinder we've beennwanting.  This would let us add custom traceback-handling support as we unwound the stack.nnAnother limitation is that tracebacks are supposed to automatically include a referencento the entire frame stack (tb.tb_frame.f_back.f_back.f_back....).  In Pyston, we're notnautomatically generating those frame objects, so we would either need to do that and takena perf hit, or (more likely?) generate the frame objects on-demand when they're needed.nnIt's not really clear that they're actually needed for traceback objects, so I implementedna different traceback object API and changed the traceback.py library, under the assumptionnthat almost-noone actually deals with the traceback object internals.n

Rearrange things to improve our ability to inline common casesWe seem to be spending a fair amount of time doing unnecessary worknfor simple calls like boxInt and createList, which are generatednby irgen and reduce to calling new BoxedInt / BoxedList.  Thenoperator new calls tp_alloc, so we get some indirect function calls,nand then tp_alloc does some checking about its caller, and then wencheck to see what size object to create, and how to initialize it.nnI created a DEFAULT_CLASS_SIMPLE macro to go with DEFAULT_CLASS,nthat should help with these things. reduce mallocs by using llvm::SmallVector in a lot of hot pathsThere were a lot of std::vectors in the rewriter and in the invokenmachinery (callFunc and friends), and every std::vector usage involvesna call to malloc (and free when is destroyed.)  we should be usingnllvm::SmallVector wherever we can in performance sensitive code, since itnallows a configurable stack allocated buffer.  It reverts to malloc/freenif you blow the buffer's capacity, but as long as things are tuned well,nwe can get a pretty significant speedup.nnThere is more work to be done, but this change gets us ~3% on geomean.n

Rearrange some class creation and initialization functionsOur class-creation code is getting pretty unruly, since therenare four places we can create new classes:n1) extension classesn2) Python-defined classesn3) builtin-defined classesn4) classes created during bootstrappingnnThen, there are multiple different sets of initialization functionsnthat can be called, each of which initializes different sets of thenclass attributes.  It's not easy to tell what a given initializationnfunction should actually initialize.nnThis change just cleans this up slightly: it renames PystonType_Readynto commonClassSetup to hopefully be more clear about its goal, as wellnas adds a BoxedClass::finishInitialization() function.nnIt also moves some work out of the BoxedClass() constructor, sincenthis causes issues because it happens before the BoxedHeapClass()nconstructor runs, which sets certain class slots that affect othernparts of class initialization.nnThings are still pretty complicated but this should help with thenmultiple inheritance changes that are coming.n

Support multiple inheritanceThe core functionality is to calculate and store tp_mro and tp_basesninstead of just tp_base.  This gives the runtime a bit harder of antime to bootstrap itself since now a fully-built class depends onna few more classes, so the bootstrapping section got larger:n- object_cls (base of the tp_base hierarchy)n- type_cls (base of the metaclass hierarchy)n- str_cls (for ht_name)n- tuple_cls (for tp_mro)n- list_cls (for calculating the mro)nnThere were a few places that needed to be updated now that we havenmultiple inheritance:n- typeLookup()n- isSubclass()n- typeNew()n- super()nnThis change doesn't even attempt to add multiple inheritance rulesnaround old-style classes.n

Support setting __dict__It's trickier than just setting all of the attributes, since any updatesnto either the original dict or to the object's attributes will getnmirrored in the other object.  I don't know if anyone uses this,nbut I don't think there's any good way for us to tell if this isngoing to happen so we just have to be conservative.nnSo, add a new distinction between types of hidden classes, and addna new dict backed type.  Instead of having an array of attributes,nhas a single attribute which is a dict.nnThere are some pretty tricky corner cases that we don't support yet,nsuch as if you access and save __dict__, then set __dict__, and thenntry to access the saved version.  At least we can detect that and fail.n

Switch the attributes array to be a PRECISE arrayPreviously it was UNTRACKED and the object's gcHandler would scannit if necessary. add StatTimer, a lightweight cpu tick timerEach thread has a stack of timers (which should have automatic scope.)  pushing a timernonto the stack pauses the currently running one to avoid double counting, and popping antimer resumes the previous one.nnalso make sure we pause the current timer, and swap out the current stack of timers whennswapping to/from generator stacks, since otherwise pushes/pops won't line up and we hitnasserts in StatTimer.nnTimers and StatTimers accumulate their durations in terms of CPU ticks, which are convertednto microseconds only at Stats::dump() time, calculated with our estimate of CPU frequency.nNeedless to say, this only works when there is no CPU stepping/scaling.nnThere are some additions to the Timer class that allow us to get the start/end time so thatnwe can sync up StatTimers with them, if both are used in a given piece of code.nngetCPUTicks() is only implemented using __rdtscp() at the moment, so won't work on anythingnnot recent relatively recent x86.nnwe accumulate total ticks during dumping and output both 'ticks_in_main' and 'ticks_all_timers',nwhich should be equal.n

Add new SINGLETON hidden class typeThe storage strategy per-object is the same as NORMAL, but instead of havingnimmutable chains of hidden classes so that we can share them between instances,na SINGLETON hcls is unique to the single object that it is for.  This meansnthat it can be mutable.nnThis has the advantage that we don't have to track all the parentsnof the hidden class.  This is especially helpful since the cases thatnit's used for (Python classes and modules) tend to have a large numbernof attributes (>100 not uncommon).nnWe could also use the DICT_BACKED strategy for those cases, but compared tonDICT_BACKED, SINGLETON should have much better lookup performance sincenit is patchpoint-compatible.  Adding new attributes is probably slower,nand deleting attributes is probably much slower, but I think those arenhopefully rare.nnThis cuts non-jit 'import pip' memory by 15%, from 113MB to 98MB.n

Change our GC handling of weakrefsFor weakly-referenced objects that are garbage, we end up freeing theirnattributes within that collection (assuming they are garbage as well).nThis means that these objects are in a state that is not quite dead (wendon't want to allocate anything else in that space and clobber theirnweakreflist), and not quite alive (their attributes point to garbagenmemory).nnSo, change the handling to finish looking at those objects in the collectionnthat they become garbage, and then free them to make them properly dead.nnweakrefs-handling is unavoidably reentrant, but now we only have to worrynabout fully-dead (the referents) or fully-alive (the weakrefs) objects.n

Check destructors and weakrefs for extension objectsAdd a new allocation type CONSERVATIVE_PYTHON for extensions objects, for whichnwe don't have heap maps, but should still have Python finalization semanticsn(ie destructors and weakrefs).  Previously we were just marking them asnCONSERVATIVE and skipping them during the sweep phase, and not running destructorsnor handling weakrefs.nnIt's a bit tricky to figure out when to mark an allocation as conservative vsnconservative-python; the approach in this commit is to mark all capi-originatednallocations as conservative, and then when we call PyObject_Init or PyObject_InitVar,nswitch them from conservative to conservative-python.  I think this is more expensivenbut safer than assuming that certain apis will always/never be used as objectnmemory.nnUnfortunately there are quite a few extension classes that request a custom tp_dealloc,nand this commit just keeps the old (bad) behavior of ignoring those.  I tried to verifynas many as I could and they all seem benign, but it will be nice to havenreal destructor support :)n
Switch to cpython's object_init and object_new

Debugging helper: invalidate freed objectsWithout this, one could use freed objects without issues,nuntil something else was allocated in that space.  And even then,nit would still be a valid object.nnSo, in debug mode overwrite the data with garbage to try to surfacenthese issues.nnThis exposed an issue with our nonheap roots handling, where wenweren't scanning all of the memory that they pointed to.  This isnmostly fine, but there are some cases (time.gmtime) where gc-allocatednmemory would be stored in these objects.  So, now you have to registernthe size of the object, and the memory range will be scanned conservatively.n

Switch to CPython's implementation of thread._localCPython's implementation has quite a bit more features than ournold one.  We only particularly need one of them (call __init__nwhen accessed from a new thread), but it looks like there arensome other features in there that have a decent chance of bitingnus in annoying ways (some gc-related stuff).nnThat implementation forced some of the other work in this PR, ofnsupporting weakrefs on extension objects (which this uses), andnmaking object.tp_init get set the same way it does in CPython.n
Switch to CPython's format for PyCFunctionObjectWe were using a slightly different (flattened) version; not sure why.n

Update isValidGCObject to check the allocation kindie make sure both that it's a valid allocation, but also thatnit will have Python destructor semantics applied when it is freedn(as opposed to, say, STLCompatAllocator-allocated memory).nnThis is to make sure that extension modules don't use a differentnallocation routine than we expected.nnThere are only a few specialized places that I could find that wenactually want the old-behavior; in dump(), and in PyObject_Init rightnbefore we call setIsPythonObject.  So for those cases, add a newnisValidGCMemory call that doesn't do the allocation-kind check.n

build tracebacks incrementally while c++ unwindingAdd a tb_next to the BoxedTraceback object, which during normal unwinding is how we add lines to a traceback.nFor getTraceback() we take advantage fo the fact that each BoxedTraceback can have multiple lines in it, andnonly create one.  Also add BoxedTraceback::Here which is kinda like PyTraceback_Here, except that since wendon't have access to the ExcInfo inside it, we have to pass a pointer to the BoxedTraceback*.nnthree wrinkles in traceback generation while unwinding are:nn   1) if the previous frame was an osr frame (so we should skip the current frame)n   2) if the traceback object was passed to raise3, or raise0 was used (treated as a re-raise by cpython)n   3) the interpreter mapnn1 and 2 are fixed by keeping a per-thread interpreter state variable, unwind_why (why is probablyna bad name to use in this context, but cpython's logic uses that word as well), to record if we're inneither of those cases.  Both cases have the same effect (skip the next traceback line, and reset statento NORMAL.)nnThe interpreter map problem comes about because of the way c++ unwinding works.  since ASTInterpreter::executenuses RAII for RegisterHelper, unwinding through the frame causes us to jump to a cleanup block and then resumenunwinding (with the IP still in ASTInterpreter::execute).  Since the IP is there, we assume the frame is validnand we can look up $rbp in the interpreter map.  Given that we just cleaned up the RegisterHelper (and removednthe $rbp mapping), we crash.nnThe fix here is to keep the same RegisterHelper in ASTInterpreter::execute, but the ip checked for by thenunwinder (and the $rbp in the mapping) correspond to ASTInterpreter::executeInner.nnLastly, AST_Interpreter::invoke catches exceptions, so we won't make it to the top-most ASTInterpreter::execute,nand so won't add the final line.  We make use of BoxedTraceback::Here here as well to add the final line.n

Support buggy callers of PyString_GET_SIZEIn CPython, PyString_GET_SIZE and PyUnicode_GET_SIZE happen to haventhe same implementation, so it is ok for callers to be wrong aboutnwhich one they call.nnFor us, previous to this commit, PyString_GET_SIZE would call PyString_Size,nwhich has different behavior than PyString_GET_SIZE for non-strings.nFor unicode objects it means that we would return the size of the encodednrepresentation of the string rather than the number of unicode characters.nIt also means that PyString_GET_SIZE can fail for us and return -1,nwhich it never can for CPython, so callers get away with notnchecking the return value.n

Add new JIT tier between the interpreter and the LLVM JIT tiers. This JIT is tightly coupled to the ASTInterpreter, at every CFGBlock* entry/exit on can switch between interpreting and directly executing the generated code without having to do any translations. Generating the code is pretty fast compared to the LLVM tier but the generated code is not as fast as code generated by the higher LLVM tiers. But because the JITed can use runtime ICs, avoids a lot of interpretation overhead and stores CFGBlock locals sysbols inside register/stack slots, it's much faster than the interpreter.

Get rid of interpreted CompiledFunctionsThis was vistigial from the old llvm interpreter, where we it made a bit morensense.  Now it's just weird, and caused the tiering logic to be spread intonweird places.  It was also the source of some bugs, since when we would deoptnthere's not really any relevant CompiledFunction that represents the deoptnframe (this is why type speculation had to be temporarily disabled).nnSo instead, make it so that the interpreter (and by extension, the baselinenjit) work on the CLFunction directly, since the CompiledFunction didn't holdnany relevant information anyway. Experimental: speed up calling of capi codeThe main capi calling convention is to box all the positionalnarguments into a tuple, and then pass the tuple to PyArg_ParseTuplenalong with a format string that describes how to parse out thenarguments.nnThis ends up being pretty wasteful and misses all of the fastnargument-rearrangement that we are able to JIT out.  These unicodenfunctions are particularly egregious, since they use a helpernfunction that ends up having to dynamically generate the formatnstring to include the function name.nnThis commit is a very simple change gets some of the common cases:nin addition to the existing METH_O calling convention ('self' plusnone positional arg), add the METH_O2 and METH_O3 callingnconventions.  Plus add METH_D1/D2/D3 as additional flags that cannbe or'd into the calling convention flags, which specify that therenshould some number of default arguments.nnThis is pretty limited:n- only handles up to 3 arguments / defaultsn- only handles O type specifiers (ie no unboxing of ints)n- only allows NULL as the default valuen- doesn't give as much diagnostic info on errornnThe first two could be handled by passing the format string as partnof the function metadata instead of using it in the function body,nthough this would mean having to add the ability to understand thenformat strings.nnThe last two issues are tricky from an API perspective since theynwould require a larger change to pass through variable-length datanstructures.nnSo anyway, punt on those issues for now, and just use the simplenflag approach.  This cuts the function call overhead by about 4xnfor the functions that it's applied to, which are some common ones:nstring.count, unicode.count, unicode.startswith.n(endswith, [r]find, and [r]index should all get updated as well)n

Add support for the __del__ slot and some refactoring.Make sure __del__ methods get assigned to tp_del in new style classes.nnGo through an attribute lookup in old style classes. Implement PyPy's finalization ordering algorithm.- Call all finalizers properly, in a safe-to-do-so order.n- Make finalizers work together with weak reference callbacks - namely,n  both should be able to get called, and weakref callbacks should ben  called before finalizers.n- Old style classes are also supported, but we always do an attributen  lookup for tp_del because there's no tp_del slot. Since it would ben  too slow to do an attribute lookup all the time in GC, we just assumen  all old-style classes have an ordered finalizer.n

Tests for finalization code.New testing helper function ensures that objects are garbagencollected and their finalizers tested in a more strict order. Thisnreduces the chances that an object isn't collected because a referencenremains in the stack, but it's hard to fully solve this problem as longnas we have conservative stack scanning.n

No-op explicit deallocations and make GCs safe inside finalizers.Make sure CPython functions like PyObject_Del do not free any objects.nIt's better to let the GC free all objects because only the GC cannguarantee that there are no more references to an object.n

Implement missing functionality for indexing and slicing.- Call either the item functions (e.g. __getitem__) or slicing functionn  (e.g. __getslice__) to match the CPython behavior.n- Implement __getslice, __setslice__, __delslice__, for lists.n- Implement __setslice__ for strings.n- Some refactoring of common functionality for indexing and slicing.n- A lot of tests.n

Handle more slicing edge cases.- Non-integer and non-None object passed into slices can fall backn  to item operator.n- Support indexeable items for slices when appropriate.n- Increase setitem and delitem ic slot sizes so that the rewriterncan succeed.n- Increase the performance of using slice operators on built-in typesn  avoiding a lot of the guards and slowpath.n

Optimize isinstanceisinstance(obj, cls) needs to do a bunch of dynamic checking: it needs toncheck cls's class to see if it defines __instancecheck__, and it needsnto fetch __class__ on obj.  Most of those time those aren't overridden,nso __instancecheck__ gets skipped and __class__ returns the type of the object.nnSo use the same type slot machinery to cache whether an __instancecheck__nor custom __class__ attribute have gotten added.  These are a bit differentnthan the other slots since they are not wrappers, they are simply boolsnthat say whether or not the attribute exists.  This makes the slot handlingncode a bit messier / more divergent from CPython, but I think it still makesnsense to put this here since we get the hooking-on-attribute-updating andnupdate-all-subclasses-as-well automatically.n

Optimize slot_tp_getattr_hookie the way that __getattr__ ends up getting called.  Two main optimizations:n- switch the initial attribute access (ie checking to see the attribute existsn  before calling __getattr__) to use a non-throwing api.  For the typical case,n  even though the throwing would be a C API throw, the construction of then  AttributeError is relatively expensive, and the object would be immediatelyn  discarded anyway.n- add rewriting to the functionnnThey both roughly cut out half the overhead of accessing attributes onnclasses with __getattr__.n

A couple rewriting fixes / improvements- rewriting a runtimeCall of an instancemethod was broken (this isn  a separate code path from the much-more-common callattr form).n- we don't need to guard on the this->cls as often in Box::getattr, specificallyn  in cases that are coming from typeLookup.  Not because the classes are fixedn  (I think they can change), but because they are not allowed to change in a wayn  that would change what Box::getattr has the guard for (guarding on attrs_offsetn  and tp_dictoffset).n- slightly change the place we guard on tp_getattro and tp_getattr to a place I thinkn  is a bit more correct (or at least easier to understand as being correct).n

Add class-level caching of whether __getattribute__ existsThis is not quite the same as checking whether tp_getattronhas been updated, since setting a __getattr__ will changentp_getattro.nnUsually this isn't that important since we will still neednto do some special getattr handling, but in a couple specificncases we can optimize based on it.  In particular, this commitnoptimizes calls to isinstance(inst, cls) on instances which havena __getattr__ set: in the common case (no __getattribute__,nno custom __class__) we can know that the __getattr__ will notnget called and we can stay on the isinstance fastpath.n

Optimize calling str() and unicode()They are tricky since these are types, which means they invokenthe relatively-complicated constructor logic.  ie str() doesn'tnjust call __str__ on the argument: if the result is a subclassnof str, it calls result.__init__(). PyArg_ParseSingle could be further optimized ifnwe want to.  Or rather, if we have functions of the formnPyArg_ParseSingle_s (which corresponds to the s format code) wencould skip some more of the overhead.nnI had to disable most of that once I realized the encoding issue, butnI left it in since hopefully we will be able to use it again oncenwe have some do some guards after mutations if we know how to resumenafter a failed guard rewriter support.n

Change how the llvm jit passes exceptions between blocksOur IR doesn't explicitly represent the data transfer between an Invokenstatement and its corresponding LandingPad.  We use a couple differentntechniques to pass it through: in the ast interpreter/bjit, we stash itninto an interpreter-local variable and then pull it back out.  Previousnto this change, in the LLVM tier we would pass it directly throughnan exception, using either the C++ or CAPI exception-passing mechanism.nnThis works but is a pain, since it requires coordination between the invokenand the landingpad.  These live in different basic blocks, so we ended upnhaving this other code that lives separate from the normal irgen that hasnto decide which exception style to use, and it has to respect certainnrestrictions within irgen (ie it has to be careful to not request CAPInexceptions for cases that we haven't added support for yet).nnThis commit changes the approach so that the exception data is passedndirectly as LLVM Values, and its up to the Invoke to figure out hownto get it into that form.  This adds a bit more complexity to the invoke,nbut it should make the interface easier to extend (such as in the next commit).n

Factor out the C stack->Python stack conversionWe have a couple different ways of walking the C stackn(C++ exception unwinding and non-destructing stack crawling),nand they both want to do this to reconstruct the Python stack.nExtract out the common code.n

Move a bunch of stuff out of UnwindSessionIt was pretty unwieldy and handled some disparate parts of thenexception-raising process.  I think things are a bit cleaner now:n- cxx_unwind.cpp handles C++ unwinding semanticsn- unwinding.cpp converts C stacks to Python stacksn- exceptions.cpp takes Python stack frames and handles them appropriatelynnSo for throwing a C++ exception, it starts out in cxx_unwind.cpp, whichnthen hands off the C frames to unwinding.cpp, which then hands off thenPython frames to exceptions.cpp.  When we get exceptions not via uncaughtnC++ exceptions (ie explicitly handled C++ exceptions or CAPI exceptions),nthose go directly into exceptions.cpp.  There are also non-exception casesnthat we want to get the Python stack trace (ex sys._getframe), and thosenare handled by unwinding.cppn

Fix inheriting extension classes from builtinsPreviously, we would just call these conservative python objects,nand scan their memory conservatively.  The problem with this is thatnthe builtin type might have defined a custom GC handler that needs tonbe called in addition to the conservative scanning (ie it stores GCnpointers out-of-band that are not discoverable via other gc pointers).nnWe had dealt with these kinds of issues before which is why I addednthe conservative python kind, but I think the real solution here isnto say that to the GC, these objects are just python objects, andnthen let the type machinery decide how to scan the objects, includingnhow to handle the inheritance rules.  We were already puttingnconservativeGCHandler as the gc_handler on these conservative types,nso let's use it.n

Add a getattr rewrite return conventionPreviously, we would inspect the combination of (return_value, exception_state)nto try to determine what the behavior of future rewrites will be.  For example,nif no attribute was returned and no exception was thrown, then we would assumenthat all future times through the rewrite the behavior would be the same.  Thisnhas caused a few bugs, and I'm about to add other cases where it won't be possiblento examine the current function's return value to determine what the futurenrewrites will do.nnSo instead, have getattr-like functions return a rewriter return convention flagnthat says how future rewrites will behave.n

Rewriter aggressiveness and backoffAdd a concept of rewriter aggressiveness that decreases over time.nIt starts off high and we will try to rewrite everything fully, butnas we succeed too often (megamorphic) or fail to rewrite, we willndecrease the aggressiveness and produce more generic rewrites.  Thisnmeans they are more likely to succeed both at the rewriting stagenand at the execution stage.n

Back off of rewriting runtimecall in callattrWe often have cases where the attr part of a callattr can be rewritten butnthe call part cannot.  This change lets us be able to rewrite the getattrnand then write out the call as a call just to runtimeCallInternal.n

dict: the gc can resurrect objects after deallocso object's can be resurrected even with a non-resurrectingntp_dealloc.  The only thing that can happen at that point isnthat the gc_visit function will get called.nnThis shows up in the new sqlalchemy tests: they use a subclassnof dict (defaultdict), which defines a custom tp_dealloc.  We call that,nwhich ends up calling dict_cls->tp_dealloc, which calls ~DenseMapnon the internal DenseMap.  The GC will accidentally keep the objectnalive (via a stack reference or something similar), and call itsnvisit function on the next GC.  But ~DenseMap does not leave the mapnin a consistent state, so iterating over it will end up producingngarbage values.  To solve this, add a new function that doesnall the same memory-freeing, but does a tiny bit of extra work to keepnthe DenseMap in a valid state for future gc_visit calls.n

fix a very bad stack map bug where symbolic entries could end up having the wrong location offset My sym entry llvm stackmap patch contains a bug where it will emit stackmap entries with the wrong offset into the large constants array. The problem is that the code assumes that the symbolic stack map constants are emitted at the end of the constants array, but doen't take into consideration that normal large constants can be added after symbolic entries. Thereby making the assigned offsets point to the wrong constants. To fix this issue I'm calculating the offset for symbolic entries now at the very end when we know that the number of constants can't change anymore. A nicer fix would be to not emit the symbolic entries inside the large cosntants array but instead into a special one. But I think this is overkill for now and would like to todo this when the stackmap v2 code landed inside llvm in order to not have to implement it twice.

new frame introspection using vregs for non compiler generated names This splits up the handling of deopts and normal frame introspection (e.g. for a traceback). We have to add to nearly all call sites frame introspection which makes it very important that it does not introduce much overhead over a normal call instruction. By always storing the user visible variables into a vregs array (layout the same as in the interpreter/bjit) we can make introspection cheaper. Frame introspection only needs to access user facing variables therefore we don't have to generate extra bytes for spilling variables which get clobbered in the callee because all values we need to access are inside the vregs array. This let's use remove the 95byte overhead and reduces the stackmap size. It adds a slight cost of maintaining the vregs array but we were already doing some of this work before with our manual spilling with the additional benefit of faster frame introspection.The deopts case stays pretty much the same with the exception that we don't add the user visible vars to the stackmap because they are already in the vreg.nWe could reduce the overhead by implementing a special deopt() function in asm which stores and restores all variables thereby we would not have to manualy spill the registers when filling the deopt IC.nAlternatively we could handle it inside llvm by either switching to a stackmap intrinsic which already supports this case or adding it it does not exist...nBut I think it's not worth it because deopts should be uncommen...n

Don't generate patchpoints for calls to fixed functions which don't need patching Previously we generated patchpoints for every call because the callee could do a frame introspection and we could not retrieve the frame info without the additional patchpoint informations.This change moves all required information inside the FrameInfo.nBecause the FrameInfo does not have a fixed offset (different num of stack args and OSR functions reuse the frame info from the interpreter),nwe generate at function entry a stack variable which points to the frame_info and than we emit a stackmap intrinsicnin order to know which basepointer relative address it has.nThe current statement inside the FrameInfo gets only updated on direct calls - patchpoints still attach it directly instead of updating the memory.nBecause always updating the variable is a small slowdown.nnThis allows us todo inlining of trivial call sites at the llvm IR level.n

add frame intospection for exited frames this works by copying the last locals state into the BoxedFrame when we exit a function. As a perf improvement we only create BoxedFrames if _getframe got called or an exception got thrown.It turned out that our python frame retrieving / updating code was really slow (using libunwind) I replaced it now withna approach which manually keeps track of the python frames (calling initFrame/deinitFrame every time a functions gets called / exits).nSadly we can't inline this functions in the llvm tier currently because it uses thread local storage which the JIT does not support.nBut I have a prototype which works around the issue with inline asm.nWe also store now always the current stmt inside the FrameInfo and in addition the FunctionMetadata.nThis made it possible to switch away from libunwind frame introspection for most cases (except deopt and c++ unwinding where we need to access all register)nnI think we can further improve the patch in several ways:n - only copying the vregs array instead of generating the dict which takes more time (because of space overhead and hashing?).n - refcounting should remove uneccesarry locals updating when no one keeps track of the BoxedFrame anymore.n - switch to cpythons traceback implementationn

bjit: don't directly do a OSR from the bjit We can't directly do OSR from the bjit frame because it will cause issues with exception handling. Reason is that the bjit and the OSRed code share the same python frame and the way invokes are implemented in the bjit. During unwinding we will see the OSR frame and will remove it and continue to unwind but the try catch block inside ASTInterpreter::execJITedBlock will rethrow the exception which causes another frame deinit, which is wrong because it already got removed. Instead we return back to the interpreter loop with special value (osr_dummy_value) which will trigger the OSR from there.
bjit: microptimization use r13 instead of r12 for the interpreter pointer saves a few bytes because r12 requires the SIB byte django_template bjit bytes emitted shrinks from 3016247 to 3006353

Fix refcounting of array-passed argsSometimes to pass a variable number of argument we allocate an array, storenthe arguments in that array, and then pass the array as the single C-levelnarg.  This caused ref issues where the refcounter thought that the variablesnwere dead after the store -- ie before the function call -- and it wouldndecref them right then.  This commit adds a refUsed hook that allows usnto specify these sorts of non-IR-based uses.nnAnother option would have been to make the arrays fully refcounted (ie thenarray itself is treated as owning references to its contents), but in thisncase I think that's overkill since it's really just an ABI issue that thenrefcounter didn't understand.n

Generate cxx fixups on-demandfixups aka the stubs that decref whatever's needed when an exception is thrownnnI looked into this because most (75%?) of the refcounting overheadncomes from the cxx fixups.  Previously we would always generate them innthe IRGenerator, regardless of whether they were needed.  Now they arengenerated in the refcounter, which knows whether they are needed or not.nnUnfortunately it looks like they are usually needed, so the gains herenaren't that great (saves about 10% llvm instructions whereas cxx fixupsnin general added about 400% more llvm instructions).nnI think this is still a good change because it's also necessary in order to usenMarius's EH stuff.nnI think the cost of the fixups is mostly related to the cost of the decrefsnthat it adds, so even though most of the refcounting overhead seems to be due tonadding the cxx fixups, reducing general decref overhead might reduce cxx fixup overheadn

Low-tech optimization: add xdecrefAll() functionFor use on the exception path. Butneven if I turn off cxx fixups entirely it still takes 2.9s.n

Use patchpoints to skip decref jit overheadRepresent decref/xdecref operations as opaque functions calls.nI think the ideal solution would be to add a custom llvm intrinsic,nbut I spent a small amount of time looking into that and had troublenfiguring out how to do that.nnSo instead, just emit them as patchpoints, and then patch them afterwardsnwith a fixed code sequence.nnThis commit only does this for decref/xdecref because:n- they occur much more frequentlyn- they are much more expensive to jit since they involve control flown- forcing the op to fit a C-calling-convention isn't that much overhead,n  since the register allocator probably would have done that anyway duen  to the (potential) dealloc call.n

Fix deinitFrame on deoptOur convention is that on deopt, the callee is responsible for calling deinitFrame().nThis is tricky, since for OSR our convention is the opposite, that the caller calls deinitFrame().nnThis means that if we OSR and then deopt(), the top and bottom frames both think they should callndeinitFrame() (since one is the caller of an OSR and the other is the callee of a deopt).nnThis commit fixes + extends the disable deinitFrame for this frame approach we kind of had.nFor performance, deinitFrame() stays the same, but any site that might have its deinitFrame disabledn(namely, in the interpreter), it should call deinitFrameMaybe() instead.n

Add some lifetime information to temporaries in the cfgBy adding a 'is_kill' flag to AST_Name nodes, which say thatnthis is the last use of this name.  This handles some common casesnof keeping temporaries alive for too long.nnFor some rare cases, there is no AST_Name that is a last use:nfor example, the iterator object of a for loop is live afternevery time it is used, but dies when exiting the loop.nnFor those, we insert a `del #foo` instead.nnThe interpreter and bjit use these flags to remove temporariesnfrom the vregs.nnThe LLVM jit ignores them since it has its own way of handlingnlifetime.  It ignores any `del` statements on temporary namesnas an optimization.nnThis does not handle decref'ing temporaries on an exception.n

Add RewriterVar::replaceAttr()Previously, to replace a refcounted object in memory, we would do something likennarray->getAttr(offset)->setType(OWNED);narray->setAttr(offset, new_val);nnThe problem is that this ends up emitting something likenx = array[offset];nPy_DECREF(x);narray[offset] = new_val;nnwhich is not safe, since x can have a destructor that runs.nIn this particular case, the destructor changed the value of array[offset].nnIt's actually pretty hard to get the right behavior (decref after setting thennew value) from outside the rewriter class, so add a new replaceAttr that doesnthese steps.n

Another run-arbitrary-code-during-unwinding issueThis time it was from trying to look at the result of isUnwinding()nto determine if the function terminated successfully or via an exception.n(And in the exception case, to decref some values that would have been returned.)nnThis got tripped up in a case where we through an exception, this triggersnan AUTO_DECREF which takes an object to zero decrefs, which has a custom destructor,nand calls code that ends up calling isUnwinding().  This is all happening from insidena C++ destructor, so this counts as isUnwinding().nnWe had some code to try to keep isUnwinding() meaning what we wanted to use it for,nbut it was only for certain cases.  I think we might be able to extend it to more cases,nbut it seems like that would be a losing battle since it's hard to say when unwindingnends and then we are suddenly not unwinding.nnSo instead, I just disabled isUnwinding() (except in debug mode where it can be somewhatnuseful for writing assert(foo || isUnwinding())), and then used a different way tontry to determine if the function exited normally.n

Smart leak checkerPreviously we would print out all leaked objects at program exit.nBut this is problematic since it includes both directly leaked objectsn(the ones we are interested in), and indirectly leaked objectsn(which only got leaked by being referenced from another leaked object).nnThis uses the cycle collector infrastructure to figure out what objectsnhave non-heap, ie leaked, references remaining. Interpreter: refcount safety for signalsWe would leak refs if an exception was thrown via the pending-calls handler.n

llvm JIT: refcount safety for signalsThe IR we generated looked something like this:nn1: i64 %a = doIC()n2: checkPendingCalls()n3: Box* %b = (Box*)%bnnThe problem is that the refcounter only knew about %b, starting onnline 3.  So for line 2, the refcounter didn't think it needed to decrefn%a if an exception was thrown.nnSo the first thing this commit does is it adds check that when we refcount-trackna value, if it is a cast, then the cast must be right next to the thing it is casting.nThis is stricter than we need but it should be easy enough to do and be sufficient.nnAnother approach would have been to have the refcount checker be able to track thennon-box-like values, ie track %a in the above example.  This would need some checkingnto make sure that people didn't forget to track that.  In the end I thought this wouldnbe simpler.nnThe second thing is it adds a helper function createAfter that inserts the cast innthe right location.  This could have worked by having createIC do the casting itself.nBut this was a little bit tricky since some callers want to know the Instruction of thencall itself, and if createIC only returned the cast then those would get confused.  Itncould have returned both, but that seemed complicated.n

ICs: variable size IC slots before this change we had a fixed number of equal size slots inside an IC. Because of the large difference in rewrite sizes a fixed slot size is not ideal. We often ended up with too large slots which prevented us from emitting more slots. (or very large ICs in general which are bad for memory usage and the instruction cache)With this commit we will start with a single slot with the size of the whole IC and then decreasing its size to the actual bytes emittednand creating a new slot which starts directly at the end of the previous slot.nWe will repeat to to this until the space left is smaller than the number of bytes the last slot required.nThis makes it a little bit less likely that we will be successful in overwritting an existing slotnbut our benchmarks show that it is still a large win on all our benchmarks.nnSome notable changes are:n- we pick the slot to rewrite much earlier now and prevent it from getting rewritten while we rewrite using num_inside = 1n  the reason is that we would otherwise not know how big the slot isn- when we resize a slot we have to patch the failing guard jumps to the address of the next slotn

Support asynchronous exceptionsA function at risk of naive misuse, it is only accessible via the C API.nnThis commit adds basic support for it using the same mechanism we use fornsignals.  We also have the GIL-check mechanism, but that would be a bit morenwork to get working right now due to the fact that our GIL-checks don't supportnthrowing exceptions.  Doing the async-exc check during signal checking meansnthat we will throw the async exc faster than CPython does.  It also meansnthat there are some pathological cases where with a lot of threads and a lotnof async excs we will probably have much worse performance.  But as long as theynare rare I think this commit shouldn't add any steady-state performance costs.n

BST: convert all nodes to directly operate at vregs instead of names **basic design:** This PR changes our BST nodes to directly operate on vregs instead of pointers to other nodes and names (except a few exceptions: `BST_Invoke`, `BST_MakeFunction` and `BST_MakeClass` which still needs to get converted). Most nodes got a destination vreg and one or more source vregs. Currently all of them are 32bit long but I plan to store them more compact very soon. Some nodes support a variable size of operands (e.g. the tuple node) but the size can't change after creating the node. I removed several unneeded opcodes and split a lot of nodes into separate opcodes (it may make sense to split them even further in the future). Generally all instructions except `CopyVReg` kill the source operand vregs except if the source is a ref to a constant. If one needs the preserve the source vreg on needs to create a new temporary using the `CopyVReg` opcode.There is a special vreg number: `VREG_UNDEFINED = std::numeric_limits<int>::min()`.n- when it's set as an operand vreg: it means that this is a not-set optional argument. (e.g. for a slice which only has `lower` set, `upper` would be `VREG_UNDEFINED`)n- if it's the destination it's means the result value should get immediately killed (e.g. `invoke 15 16: %undef = %11(%14)` this is a call whose result gets ignored)nnall other negative vreg numbers are indices into a constant table (after adding 1 and making them positive).n(e.g. `(4, 2, 'lala')` generates:  `%undef = (%-1|4|, %-2|2|, %-3|'lala'|)` this creates a tuple whose elements are the constant idx -1, -2 and -3. In order to make it easier for a human to understand we print the actual value of the constant between | characters)n- constants can be all str and numeric types and 'None'.n- every constant will only get stored once in the tablennthis reduces the total memory usage by about 20% currently but I'm very sure with the future changes it will be significantly lower.nn**near future:**n- change the jump and branch instruction to reference `CFGBlocks` by index.n- store all `InternedString` inside a table and use indices into the the table to access them.n- remove the 'BoxedCode*' membern- devirtualize the classesn= with this changes the bytecode can get freely copied around (only need to update the CFGBlock table) which allows us to attach the directly next to each other.nn- I plan to use one bit of the the opcode to mark the instruction as only requiring 8bit vreg operands (which should handle the majority of cases with 128 temps and 127 constants + 1undef vreg value)n- another bit will get used to specify if this instruction is inside an `invoke`. if this bit is set there are 2 one 1 or 4 bytes long block indices directly behind the instruction.nn- serialize the bytecode to disk. (maybe serialize the constants using pickle)nn**thing which need to get improved**n- currently the constant table get's attached to the `BoxedModule` maybe there is a better location, I also needed to pass the `BoxedModule` into some functions e.g. BST printing because otherwise we could not pretty-print the constantsn- `BST_Name` is not an opcode it's just used to initialize the arguments when a function get's called and stores where and how the arguments need to get stored.n- more consistent opcode names and rename `TmpValue` to something bettern- we currently don't print the `InternedString` name - we only print the vreg numbernn**additional changed made which are hidden in the large diff** :-1:n- removed unused code initializing the items of `BST_Dict` (we use/used separate  assignments to add the items)n- lower `ExtSlice` inside the CFG phase to a tuple of slicesn- separated opcode for load subscript when it needs to be a slice and when it's only lower and upper (=`__getslice__`) before this got handled in the interpreter/jitn- generate a constant `None` load inside the CFG when `None` gets loaded by namen

We can then put this into the test file, andnwhen the test fails we can run the received output against the expectednbloom filter.nnI tried testing it and it seems ok, but we'll have to see how well itnworks in practice.n
